explanation:
For determining whether any pointer in OS_SocketOpen should be const-qualified you must know which pointers are used as inputs (read-only) vs outputs or mutated. The following symbols are required and why:

- osal_id_t (typedef): sock_id is of type osal_id_t *; to decide if this pointer could be const the type semantics must be known (is it an output id that the function writes to?).

- OS_SocketDomain_t (typedef) and OS_SocketType_t (typedef): these parameter types are assigned into the internal record. Knowing whether these are scalar/value types (and whether they are modified) helps determine if any pointer-to-these-types would be better const. (Confirms they are values, not pointers.)

- OS_object_token_t (typedef): token is passed by address to multiple routines; the token type definition helps determine whether the functions modify the token contents or only read it, which affects whether pointers to it could be const.

- OS_stream_internal_record_t (struct/typedef): stream points to this type and the code writes into it (memset and field assignments). Its definition shows which fields are mutable and whether the pointer must be non-const.

- OS_stream_table (object table variable) and OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET (macro/function): OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET(OS_stream_table, token) yields the stream pointer. You need the table symbol and the macro/function definition to know the exact return type (pointer to const or non-const) and whether accessing the table is intended to produce a modifiable pointer.

- OS_CHECK_POINTER (macro): used to validate sock_id; its prototype/definition indicates whether it accepts a const-qualified pointer or requires a non-const pointer (some pointer-check macros take void const *). This impacts whether sock_id could be const in the API.

- OS_ObjectIdAllocateNew (function declaration/signature): called as OS_ObjectIdAllocateNew(LOCAL_OBJID_TYPE, NULL, &token). Its signature and documentation show whether it writes/initializes token (i.e., token is an output) and whether it mutates other arguments; this determines whether &token must be non-const.

- OS_ObjectIdFinalizeNew (function declaration/signature): called with return_code, &token, sock_id. Its signature and behavior reveal whether it writes into *sock_id (making sock_id an output) and whether it modifies token. If it writes *sock_id then sock_id must remain non-const.

- OS_SocketOpen_Impl (function declaration/signature): called with &token. Need to know if the implementation modifies the token or other pointed-to data; if it only reads token then a const qualifier could be considered, otherwise not.

Knowing these types/signatures/macros lets the next analyst determine which pointer parameters are truly input/read-only and thus candidates for const qualification vs those that are outputs or intentionally modified and therefore must remain non-const.
